 Preamble

 The GNU General Public License is a free, copyleft license for software and other kinds of works.

 When we talk about free software, we are referring to freedom, not price. Our General Public
 Licenses are designed to make sure that you have the freedom to distribute copies of free software
 (and charge for this service if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you want it,
 and that you can change the software and use pieces of it in new free programs.  To protect your
 rights, we need to make restrictions that forbid distributors to deny you these rights or to ask you
 to surrender these rights. These restrictions translate to certain responsibilities for you if you
 distribute copies of the software, or if you modify it.

 For example, if you distribute copies of such a program, whether gratis or for a fee, you must pass on
 the same freedoms to the recipients that you received. You must make sure that they, too, receive or
 can get the source code. And you must show them these terms so they know their rights.

 Developers that use the GPL protect your rights with two steps: (1) assert copyright on the software,
 and (2) offer you this License giving you legal permission to use, distribute and modify it.

 There are many people who use the GPL correctly, but there are also many who do not. Sometimes
 they will make the software proprietary by adding restrictions. Sometimes they will create a
 modified version that has even fewer rights. To prevent this, we have made this License
 explicitly for software and other kinds of works.
 The licenses for the most widely used free software are designed to make sure that everyone who
 receives a copy of the software is given access to the source code and is free to change it.

 In this way, you can provide the same freedoms to everyone else. For the sake of simplicity, we
 will call this kind of license a "GPL".  This version of the GPL was made for software. And it is
 for your right to use, modify and distribute free software.  In return, each user makes a contribution
 to improve its corresponding project.  This contribution is fixed by copyright law and can be used
 by anyone that wants to maintain a project or to pay for the creation of GPL-compatible software.

 There is no warranty for you or anyone, for using the software, but if you make any claims or
 create restrictions, the copyrights define the limits of that freedom.

 While this License is in effect, you may not use other GNU Licenses. 

